We have hele a parenthesis and an anacolouthon. The parenthesis (multi ...pulcnzda est) is inserted to meet a possible objection‚ viz.—all believe in the gods, it is true, but why do they not agree in their belief? The anacolouthon consists 111 this—to the ut-clause (ut porro...) an ita clause should correspond, but the insertion of a parenthesis often leads, as here, to the omission of the second limb of the sentence, often to its modification. Kiih. holds that ancient writers of dialogues (e.g. Plato, Cicero) did not fall into such constructions through negligence, but purposely sought to imitate in them the natural turns of conversation.
